WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.100 --> 00:00:01.884
WHAT IS AN API HOW

2
00:00:01.884 --> 00:00:05.147
It Works An API, or Application Programming Interface, is

3
00:00:05.147 --> 00:00:07.288
a set of rules and protocols

4
00:00:07.288 --> 00:00:09.786
that allows different software applications to communicate

5
00:00:09.786 --> 00:00:13.452
with each other. Think of it as

6
00:00:13.452 --> 00:00:15.236
a waiter in a restaurant

7
00:00:15.236 --> 00:00:18.447
who takes your order from the kitchen and brings

8
00:00:18.447 --> 00:00:18.507
it back to you. The kitchen is

9
00:00:18.507 --> 00:00:21.005
like the server, you are the client,

10
00:00:21.005 --> 00:00:22.789
and the waiter is the

11
00:00:22.789 --> 00:00:24.196
API. APIs work through a request

12
00:00:24.196 --> 00:00:26.982
and response model. When a client

13
00:00:26.982 --> 00:00:29.837
application wants to access data or functionality from

14
00:00:29.837 --> 00:00:33.048
a server, it sends a request to the API.

15
00:00:33.112 --> 00:00:34.896
This request contains specific information

16
00:00:34.896 --> 00:00:37.394
about what the client wants to do.

17
00:00:37.962 --> 00:00:40.103
The API then processes this request

18
00:00:40.103 --> 00:00:42.244
and forwards it to the server.

19
00:00:42.524 --> 00:00:44.665
The server performs the requested operation

20
00:00:44.665 --> 00:00:47.163
and sends back a response to the

21
00:00:47.163 --> 00:00:50.017
API, which then delivers it to the client.

22
00:00:49.962 --> 00:00:51.746
The most common type of

23
00:00:51.746 --> 00:00:53.530
API is called REST, which

24
00:00:53.530 --> 00:00:57.295
stands for Representational State Transfer. REST APIs use

25
00:00:57.295 --> 00:00:59.436
standard HTTP methods like GET, POST,

26
00:00:59.436 --> 00:01:04.169
PUT, and DELETE to perform different operations. GET

27
00:01:04.169 --> 00:01:07.023
is used to retrieve data, POST to create

28
00:01:07.023 --> 00:01:09.878
new data, PUT to update existing data, and

29
00:01:09.878 --> 00:01:12.809
DELETE to remove data. When you use an API,

30
00:01:12.809 --> 00:01:14.593
you typically need to include

31
00:01:14.593 --> 00:01:17.447
authentication credentials, often in the form of an

32
00:01:17.447 --> 00:01:19.231
API key or access token.

33
00:01:19.487 --> 00:01:22.698
This helps the server identify who is making the

34
00:01:22.698 --> 00:01:24.839
request and ensure they have permission

35
00:01:24.839 --> 00:01:26.623
to access the requested resources.

36
00:01:26.737 --> 00:01:29.591
Many APIs also use rate limiting to prevent

37
00:01:29.591 --> 00:01:31.732
abuse and ensure fair usage among

38
00:01:31.732 --> 00:01:34.020
all users. APIs return data

39
00:01:34.020 --> 00:01:36.518
in various formats, with JSON being the

40
00:01:36.518 --> 00:01:40.171
most popular. JSON is lightweight and easy

41
00:01:40.171 --> 00:01:41.955
for both humans and machines

42
00:01:41.955 --> 00:01:44.270
to read and parse. It uses key-value

43
00:01:44.270 --> 00:01:46.411
pairs to represent data in a

44
00:01:46.411 --> 00:01:49.622
structured way that can be easily transmitted over the

45
00:01:49.622 --> 00:01:52.385
internet. Real-world examples of APIs include Google Maps

46
00:01:52.385 --> 00:01:55.239
API for embedding maps, Twitter API for accessing

47
00:01:55.239 --> 00:01:58.093
social media data, Payment APIs like Stripe for

48
00:01:58.093 --> 00:02:01.305
processing transactions, and Weather APIs for retrieving forecast information.

49
00:02:04.737 --> 00:02:06.521
APIs have revolutionized software development

50
00:02:06.521 --> 00:02:09.732
by enabling different applications to work together seamlessly, creating

51
00:02:09.732 --> 00:02:12.230
interconnected digital ecosystems that power the modern

52
00:02:12.230 --> 00:02:12.587
internet.

